description: I was enjoying a lunch on the back deck of River View Restaurant & Lounge when I seen these small birds flying from their perches in the trees to rocks on the edge and in the middle of the river. When the bird would land on the rocks that were precariously close to the water's torrent they would edge themselves closer and closer to the edge. Then all of a sudden "bloop" the little bird was gone, and instantly I knew what I was observing. I had never seen an American dipper before, but I am not aware of too many birds that have that behavior. I was amazed by their boldness, being able to dive into what I perceived to be a rapid current of water didn't seem to phase the little bird at all.

Elevation approximately 7,400' or 2,250 m. This is the lowest I've seen a pika colony in the Sierra Nevada. The end of the Tokopah Falls trail from Lodgepole Camp passes right through the start of their talus habitat, and this picture is from right next to the trail. The talus here is adjacent to riparian and shrub dominated habitats, with woods also nearby.

description: Mother bear and four cubs walking across the crystal cave road.

I THINK it's a coyote, but it's larger, with a fuller coat than any coyote I've seen (I see them almost daily). Certainly, it looks very well adapted to the environment. There is ample food supply, in marmots, other small rodents, possibly birds and trout, possibly occasional deer, etc. Exact elevation of sighting was 12,126 feet, verified by my altimeter, on top of a ridge between two lakes; alpine, well above tree line. Absolutely stunning sight. I am a regular traveler in the high Sierra, off trail, and have never seen such a sight. I've heard coyotes elsewhere in the Sierra, somewhat lower, but never in such an exposed site.

It was moving around the base of the Ed by Ned Tree on the Big Trees Trail loop around Round Meadow in the Giant Forest area of Sequoia National Park. Note the photo timestamp in the metadata is off an hour because my camera wasn't adjusted for DST - observation occurred at about 4:30pm on 31 Aug 2019. It stood up once to look around (captured that on video), and seemed to be looking around a lot, probably due to all the Labor Day weekend people noise.
